My wife's going to her mother's for a couple of weeks. She lives by the sea, you know.    A: Oh, does she? That's convenient.    B: Yes, but I want to go to the country.    A: Don't you like the sea?    B: Yes, very much. But I need peace and quiet when I'm on holiday.

A: Hello, John. How was your French exam yesterday?    B: Not too good.    A: Well, the term exam is always more difficult. Work harder, and you'll certainly do better next time.    B: I've worked hard enough, I think, but unluckily, I have never done well in the exam.    A: Well, it's no use worrying about the exam now. Let's talk about the football game tonight. It's much more interesting.    B: Is there a football game on TV tonight?    A: Yes it's between the Chinese team and the Japanese team.    B: ... Er I'd rather watch some other programmes.    A: Why? You're so interested in football.    B: The Chinese team has always played badly in the important match, just as I have done in the important exam.

triplets.head: Chinese team has always played badly

utterances: A: Hello, Kate. Have you been to the new sports center yet?    B: Not yet. Where is it?    A: On Mill Road, near Stone Street, behind Santa Station.    B: What about it?    A: It's wonderful. You can do a lot of sports there. I played table tennis last Saturday, and watched a basketball match.    B: What about the swimming pool?    A: It's very good. Would you like to go there with me next week?    B: Good idea. Every day is OK except Monday.    A: Well. Why not go there on Saturday? Then we can stay for a long time.    B: OK. See you.

A: Hello, Lucy. When are you going off to Beijing?    B: This evening.    A: How are you getting there, by air or by train?    B: By train. It leaves at 5:00 and arrives in Beijing at 7:10 tomorrow morning.    A: Oh, only 14 hours. Is anybody seeing you off this evening?    B: Yes, my parents are going with me to the station to see me off.    A: That's good! How long are you staying in Beijing for your holiday?    B: Only four days. Well, I must be off now. See you when I get back.    A: OK. Good luck and have a good trip!    B: Thanks. Goodbye!

triplets.head: going with me to the station

utterances: A: Hello, Macy Agency.    B: Good morning. I'd like to book a return ticket from London to Paris on Monday, July 14th, please.    A: Yes, Madam. We have a flight at 14: 30, Is that suitable?    B: Oh, that's fine. And how much will that cost, please?    A: The price is $ 420 for the return flight.    B: Good. Which airport does the flight leave from?    A: It leaves from Heathrow Airport. Check in time is one hour before departure.    B: My name is Susan Smith. Can I pick up the ticket tomorrow morning?    A: Sure, we'll have it ready soon, so come whenever you like after that.    B: Thank you.    A: You are welcome.

A: Hello, Mary.    B: Hello, Jason. What are you going to do this evening?    A: I've no idea. What about you?    B: I have two tickets for the football match. Will you go with me?    A: Certainly. You know I haven't watched a football match for a long time.    B: Neither have I Shall we go there by bus?    A: All right. After supper let's meet at the street corner. OK?    B: OK. Let's hurry up. Now it's 6:30. The match will begin in an hour. Be sure not to be late.    A: Sure, I'll get to the street corner on time.

triplets.head: haven't watched a football match for a long time

utterances: A: Hello, Mary. Why are you standing here?    B: I'm waiting for a bus. The buses are so full at this time of the day.    A: Sure. Where are you going? I don't think this is your way home.    B: You are right. I'm going for a walk in the park.    A: Going for a walk even after along day's work?    B: Yes. I always enjoy walking alone in the park after work.    A: I see. Then why not go there on foot? It's not so far from here.    B: Oh, no. I hate walking through the streets.

A: Hello, Mrs. Taylor. Can you help me? I'm doing my homework and I can't understand this word.    B: Which one? Oh, I can't help you right away...I'm watching something on TV.    A: Oh? What are you watching?    B: I'm watching a cowboy film.    A: Can Mr. Taylor help me?    B: No, he can't now, Paul. He's reading.    A: What is he reading?    B: He's reading a magazine.    A: What about Kate?    B: Oh, she can't help you either. She's making a phone call now.    A: Oh? Who's she calling?    B: She's calling her boyfriend.    A: Then where is Jack? Can I ask for help from him?    B: He hasn't been home yet...Why? You're asking a lot of questions tonight, Paul.    A: Am I?...Well, I'm practicing my English.

A: Hello, Ms Thomas. What can I do for you?    B: Well, I've been having bad stomach pains lately, doctor.    A: Oh, I'm sorry to hear that. How long have you been having them?    B: Just in the last few weeks. I get a very sharp pain about an hour after having meals.    A: I see. Do you get this after every meal?    B: Let me think. No, it's usually in the afternoon, after lunch.    A: Well, what do you have for lunch?    B: Oh, I mostly just have a quick hamburger and rush back to the office. We're very busy at the moment.    A: Well, I don't think it's a serious thing. Maybe you eat too quickly. It's bad for your health.    B: My husband is always telling me that.    A: Anyway, I'll give you something for it and see what happens. Take the medicine three times a day.    B: After meals or before?    A: After eating.    B: Thank you, doctor.    A: You're welcome.

A: Hello, Old English Restaurant. Can I help you?    B: Yes. I'd like to book a table for tonight.    A: Yes, sir. What time?    B: Eight o'clock.    A: Certainly. For how many people?    B: There are ten of us.    A: Ten of you! But we don't usually accept large parties, sir.    B: I know, but we are regular customers.    A: What's your name please, sir?    B: Michael Peterson.    A: Mr. Peterson...of course! That'll be all right. We'll put two tables together.    B: Thanks.    A: What food would you prefer for today, sir? We have fresh seafood tonight.    B: No. We like to eat vegetables.

A: Hello, Robert speaking.    B: Hi, it's Emma. I'm glad you're there. It's about our appointment on Wednesday morning. I'm afraid I can't make it now.    A: Oh, that's a shame.    B: I'm sorry. There was a change in my business partner's plan. And Wednesday is the only day she is able to see me.    A: That's okay. But we need to find another date.    B: I could manage sometime Thursday. How about you?    A: Sorry, I got an important meeting all day. What about Friday?    B: I'll go to an exhibition in the morning, but I could come to your office after that.    A: Great! Look forward to seeing you then. Bye!

triplets.head: change in my business partner's plan

utterances: A: Hello, School of English Studies.    B: Hello, I saw your advertisement in the newspaper. Can you give me some information, please?    A: Yes, of course. What would you like to know?    B: Well, first, how long are the courses?    A: They are 6 or 9 months long and the next course begins next Monday.    B: How many students will there be in the class? Not too many, I hope.    A: Usually, there are 15. We find that a good number.    B: OK. Now, I saw the price of the course in the newspaper, but will I have to pay for anything else?    A: Only for the textbook, which costs twelve pounds ninety-nine.    B: I see. When can I come and pay?    A: Well, the school is open from 8 am to 7 pm Monday to Friday and on Saturdays from 9 am to 1 pm.    B: OK. I see. Well, thank you very much. Goodbye.

A: Hello, Thomas Brothers.    B: Hello, this is Mike Landon here. Is Jack Cooper there by any chance?    A: I am afraid not, he is away for a day or two, back on, let's see, Monday morning.    B: Oh, well perhaps I can live a message for him.    A: Yes, of course, just a minute. Now, let's see, to Jack Cooper from Mike London.    B: No, Landon, L-a-n-d-o-n.    A: Sorry, yes, got that, and what's the message?    B: Well it's just this: could he come to a meeting on Monday afternoon at 5:00 pm?    A: That's this coming Monday, October 12th?    B: Right, it's to discuss the new factory in France.    A: Fine, I've got that. I will see that he gets it as soon as he comes in on Monday.    B: Good, thank you, goodbye.

A: Hello, Tom. I haven't seen you for some time. How are you doing?    B: Oh! Not too bad. I have been busy writing an article.    A: Really? Have you finished it?    B: Yes. I finished it yesterday.    A: Congratulations! Are you doing something this evening?    B: No, nothing important. Why?    A: Well, do you feel like going to a concert? I have two tickets.    B: Oh. Good idea. I want to do something relaxing, and I like music very much.    A: Great. I'll meet you at your house at seven. Is that OK?    B: OK! See you at seven.    A: All right. See you then.

A: Hello, Yang Mei. I hear you're going to the United States.    B: Yes. I'm going with my grandma. We're going to see my parents in New Jersey.    A: When are you leaving, then?    B: This Friday evening. Our plane leaves at seven fifteen.    A: How long will you be there?    B: Six months.    A: Six months! Do you go and see my grandparents in New York?    B: Of course, I will. I want to see as many places as I can. How can I travel?    A: Most people travel by car. The roads are very good.    B: But I don't have a car and I can't drive. Is there any other way to travel?    A: You can travel by bus. It's very cheap.    B: Can't I travel by train?    A: Yes, you can. The train is expensive in the States, but it's fast.    B: Thank you very much. Well, must be off now. See you when I get back.    A: Good luck and have a good trip!

triplets.head: going to the United States
triplets.tail: see as many places as I can

utterances: A: Hello, glad to see you. Come in, please.    B: Thanks. It looks like the party is exciting and all are in high spirits.    A: My brother, Tom is visiting me for the weekend.    B: Where is he?    A: He is sitting in the corner over there, and beside the yound woman.    B: And who is the yound woman? Uh, the woman wearing a red coat.    A: Oh, that's Ann, my piano teacher.    B: Piano teacher! I never knew you were practicing the piano.

A: Hello, this is Jonason speaking.    B: Hello, Jonason, I am Kasy. I am sorry to tell you that I may not attend your birthday party this weekend.    A: Oh, what's up?    B: Nothing much.., but...    A: What's happened then?    B: I have an important exam at that time.    A: If so, I think we can hold the party ahead of time. What do you think about it?    B: Yeah, It is a good idea. I can't agree more.    A: Great and I wish you success.    B: Thank you, happy birthday to you.

triplets.head: have an important exam
triplets.tail: hold the party ahead of time

utterances: A: Hello. Milton Hotel. Can I help you?    B: I want a reservation. Can I have it now?    A: Of course. What kind of taste do you like for your dinner?    B: I prefer Chinese dishes.    A: Would you like to sit in a smoking section, a non-smoking section or an open one?    B: A non-smoking section.    A: I'm awfully sorry, but we haven't got the section left now. Would you like to wait for a while?    B: Not at all. An open section will do, too.    A: OK. See you then.

A: Hello. This is Amy.    B: Hello, Amy. This is Tom.    A: Yes. What can I do for you?    B: I want to go to New York by train today. Would you please look up a train time for me?    A: Certainly, Hold on, please. Um... there's one at eleven p. m. It's a little late. Why don't you go there by car?    B: My car is being repaired now. I have to go there by train.    A: Do you think you have enough time?    B: Yes. I'll try it. Thank you. Bye.

A: Hello?    B: Hello. Is that Dr. Bean?    A: Yes, it is.    B: Dr. Bean, I'm making a survey for the National Research Company. I'd like to ask you a few questions about your health habits.    A: OK.    B: First question: How often do you take medicine?    A: I sometimes take aspirin, but that's all.    B: Do you take vitamins?    A: No, I never do.    B: How about exercise?    A: Well, I often play tennis or handball.    B: Do you eat any healthy food?    A: No, I just try to eat good food.    B: Well, I've finished. Thank you for your help.

A: Hello? I would like to speak to Mr. Lee.    B: This is Lee speaking.    A: This is Linda, your old friend.    B: Oh, how are you, Linda? I'm glad you called.    A: Mr. Smith wrote to me that you were coming to our city. May I see you at your hotel right away?    B: Please hold on a moment. I have to check my schedule. Yes, that's ail fight.    A: Great. I'll be there in haft an hour.    B: All right, I'll be expecting you.    A: Oh, I almost forgot. What's your room number?    B: It's the No. 311 on the second floor. Please call me if you can't find me.    A: I'll do that. See you later.

triplets.head: you were coming to our city
see you at your hotel
triplets.tail: you were coming to our city

utterances: A: Hey Jane, where are you going this weekend?    B: Hi, Bob. I'm going to the beach. 13o you want to come too?    A: Yes, that sounds like fun. Which beach are you going to?    B: I was thinking of going to Huangdao's Beach. I like to watch the sea birds and wildlife there.    A: That sounds great! When do you plan to leave?    B: Well, I think at about four o'clock on Friday.    A: Great. Where should we meet?    B: Meet me on Friday in front of my house.    A: OK, I'll see you then. Bye.

triplets.head: going to the beach
triplets.tail: watch the sea birds and wildlife

triplets.head: watch the sea birds and wildlife

utterances: A: Hey, Charlie. How was your football game the other day?    B: Great! Our team played hard and out Huasheng Team.    A: Congratulations! But hold on, there. Taishan Team, you know, is difficult to play.    B: You're right. It will be a close game. But I've got a good feeling about this game. Our team is sure to win!    A: Don't be too sure. Remember, we don't know who will win before the last game.    B: Well, let's wait and see.

A: Hey, Louise, where can I get some lunch around here?    B: There are several places. What would you like to eat?    A: I'd really like a cheeseburger and some French fries.    B: Well, there's a coffee shop on the next corner. It serves good food.    A: OK. I'll try it. Can I get you something?    B: No, I think I'll come with you. I'm longing for a nice salad.    A: Do you often have lunch at this coffee shop?    B: No, I usually bring my lunch from home and eat at my desk.

triplets.head: have lunch at this coffee shop

utterances: A: Hi! Nice to meet you, Nancy! Where were you yesterday?    B: I didn't come because I was sick.    A: You still look a little sick. You ought to go back to bed.    B: I am going home now.    A: Did you drive today?    B: Oh, No, I don't have a car.    A: I can take you home. Would you like a ride?    B: Yes. Thanks a lot. Could you stop at the chemist's on the way? I need to buy some medicine.

A: Hi, Bill, you look happy.    B: Yes, I've just seen a very funny film on TV.    A: What was it about?    B: It was about a careless man who got into trouble wherever he went. He couldn't do anything right.    A: So you like it?    B: Yes, I do. It made me laugh a lot.    A: But I'd rather see something not only interesting but also instructive.    B: Oh, Jane, don't be so serious. People sometimes need relaxation.    A: That's true. But I just think that watching TV is not just for entertainment.

A: Hi, Dave. Good to see you could come a long way. Come in.    B: Wow. Looks like the party is at a high point.    A: Yeah. And they're eating all of my food. Oh, I'd like you to meet my sister, Carol. She's visiting on the weekend.    B: Oh. Which one is she?    A: She's sitting on the sofa over there.    B: You mean the woman with long black hair?    A: That's right. Let me introduce her to you. You're both so friendly and adventurous.    B: And who's the man sitting next to her? Uh, the man wearing the suit jacket?    A: Oh, that's Bob, my ballet teacher.    B: Ballet teacher! I never knew you could do ballet.    A: I started about two months ago. Come on. I'd like you to meet them.    B: I'm coming.

A: Hi, David! Mr. Harper has just asked me if you'd finished your project yet. It was supposed to be handed in yesterday.    B: I know. I'm just finishing it now.    A: He wanted to know if we'd done them together. I said no. What's yours on? It took me ages to do mine.    B: Well, I was really lucky. I found this book all about the population in New Zealand cities.    A: Is it good?    B: Yes, it's a great book! I photocopied three chapters. There are some brilliant charts and...    A: What are you going to do with all that?    B: Well, now I'm going to copy these pages and these charts and then I'll finish my project!    A: You're not supposed to just copy the book.    B: Oh! I think Mr. Harper won't know.    A: He will know! He asked us to write a list of all the books we'd used. Remember? That's not the point anyway.    B: What is the point then?    A: Well, the point is that you're supposed to write your own project--you can't copy someone else's writing.    B: Er... er... Well, you're right. Thank you for your reminding me of that.

triplets.head: copy these pages
triplets.tail: write a list of all the books we'd used.

triplets.head: write a list of all the books we'd used.

utterances: A: Hi, David. I haven't seen you for ages. How are you getting along with your work?    B: Hi, Susan. Not so well as to be expected. I've left my position. I can't bear the rudeness of my boss any longer.    A: What are you going to do then?    B: No idea. Anyway, I've got to think about it seriously. And you?    A: I've been very successful as a dancer. I like this kind of life. It is so exciting.    B: You can't do that forever.    A: No. But I've decided to open a dance school once I've moved to the top. A lot of young dancers need better training.    B: That's a wonderful idea.

triplets.head: been very successful as a dancer
open a dance school
triplets.tail: been very successful as a dancer

triplets.head: been very successful as a dancer
left my position
triplets.tail: can't bear the rudeness of my boss

triplets.head: can't bear the rudeness of my boss

utterances: A: Hi, Jack. Who are you writing to?    B: I'm writing to my parents telling them I'll stay here this summer.    A: You're not going home? I thought you were going on a trip to Japan with your family.    B: Well, I intended to go with them, but I thought again and changed my mind.    A: Tell me. I'm interested in knowing what keeps you from joining your beloved family and staying here. It certainly is not studying.    B: No, certainly not. Michael arranged for me to work at his uncle's institution.    A: How much will you be paid?    B: Judy, I don't do it for money, but for experience. Besides, it's voluntary work.    A: You work without payment? That's really something.    B: When will you leave for home?    A: Tomorrow. We'll fly to Hawaii two days after. I really have to pack now.    B: Go then. Have a nice vacation!    A: I'll send you postcards.

A: Hi, John! I'd like to invite you to dinner this evening.    B: To dinner? What for?    A: I have passed my driving test!    B: Congratulations! I'm really glad to hear that.    A: Thank you! I have been preparing for it for half a year, you know. And I've made it at last.    B: So, where shall we have our dinner?    A: How about the Friendship Hotel? I like the food and service there.    B: I agree. I'll take you there in my car.    A: Fine. Let's go at half past six.

A: Hi, John. What are you doing here?    B: I'm waiting for the bus.    A: Where are you going?    B: I'm going to the station to meet my sister.    A: Oh, is she coming by herself?    B: Yes, the train comes in about half past four, but it's twenty past four now. I have only ten minutes!    A: How often does the bus run?    B: Every ten minutes. I missed a No. 1 bus 15 minutes ago, and the next one hasn't come yet!

A: Hi, Kangkang.    B: Hi, Jane.    A: What are you going to do this Saturday evening?    B: I'm going to a concert.    A: How exciting! Who is going to sing at the concert?    B: Xu Song. He is my favorite pop singer.    A: Where is he going to give the concert?    B: In the gym.    A: What time is it going to start?    B: At 7:30 p. m. Would you like to go with me?    A: I'd love to, but I'm going to visit my uncle.

A: Hi, Kathy, it's Jason.    B: Hi, Jason. I haven't heard from you in a while.    A: Well. I've been busy. I've started my own company.    B: Wow, what kind of business is it?    A: Just a small on-line store. I am hiring staff and I want you to come to work for me.    B: Actually, I just got started working at the old company again.    A: Oh, I didn't realize you were going back. Well, can you recommend someone else?

triplets.head: hiring staff
triplets.tail: I just got started working at the old company

triplets.head: I just got started working at the old company

utterances: A: Hi, Lily. Great graduation party, isn't it?    B: Yes, everyone here is having a good time. Any ideas for the future?    A: Well, I'm interested in finance and my uncle runs a company in Hong Kong, so I decided to go to Hong Kong University.    B: Sounds great. Hong Kong is an international financial center. You will surely go far there.    A: What about you?    B: I'd like to go to university in Beijing.    A: What do you want to take as your major, computer science or medicine?    B: I prefer medicine. It's always being my dream to be a doctor.

A: Hi, Mark. Are you in town for another job interview?    B: Yes, I'm pretty hopeful this time. I've just finished my second interview with this company.    A: That sounds great. I hope it works out for you. But wasn't it expensive just getting here?    B: No, in fact the company is paying all my expenses. They've put me up in a hotel downtown.    A: How nice! How many people are they interviewing?    B: They interviewed 16 the first time, and now four of us were chosen to go back for this interview.    A: Well, I hope it goes well. John and I would love it if you came to this area to work.    B: I would too. But my girlfriend doesn't want to leave her family. She hopes I find a job close to home.    A: Oh, What a decision. Good luck.

triplets.head: company is paying all my expenses
came to this area to work.
came to this area to work.
find a job close to home

utterances: A: Hi, Mike. What have you been up to?    B: Not much. I started exercising.    A: Trying to get in shape?    B: Yeah, and I need to start improving my health.    A: Me, too. What are you doing besides exercising?    B: That's about all.    A: I think if you eat better, it will also help a lot.    B: Sleep is important, too. I heard people who sleep an average of eight hours a day have less health problems.    A: Looks like there are a lot of things to do to stay healthy.    B: True. But I think it is worth it. When you get older, you want to be healthy and active.    A: Absolutely.

triplets.head: sleep an average of eight hours a day
sleep an average of eight hours a day

utterances: A: Hi, Mrs. Smith. Nice to see you here.    B: Hi, Mr. White. I'm here to buy a pair of shoes for Tom again.    A: He wore out the pair you bought last month?    B: Yes. Sometimes I think I should buy him a pair of iron shoes.    A: Oh, no. What you need is a pair of strong and comfortable shoes.    B: What's your suggestion?    A: Maybe you should buy him a pair of leather shoes.    B: Tom doesn't like leather shoes.    A: Then, how about sports shoes? They are strong and comfortable.    B: It seems that is the only choice. All right. I'll take your suggestion. How about this pair?    A: They are good.

triplets.head: wore out the pair you bought
wore out the pair you bought
triplets.tail: buy him a pair of iron shoes.

utterances: A: Hi, Robert, what happened to your face? It looks swollen.    B: I have to go and get my teeth filled.    A: Did it hurt?    B: I don't even want to talk about it. It killed me!    A: Well, I guess you've learned a good lesson, huh! You have to take good care of your teeth.    B: No kidding. I can't stand the pain, but the bill is too large!    A: Don't you have a dental insurance?    B: I do. but it doesn't cover everything.

triplets.head: get my teeth filled
triplets.tail: take good care of your teeth

triplets.head: It looks swollen
triplets.tail: take good care of your teeth

utterances: A: Hi, are you being helped?    B: No, I'm not. I'm interested in some gloves.    A: All our gloves are here. What do you think of this pair here? It's made of silk.    B: Hm, it looks nice, but I'd like to have something warm for the winter.    A: Maybe you would like heavy wool gloves. How about this pair?    B: I think that's what I want. How much is it?    A: It's... forty dollars.    B: It's a little expensive. Do you think it's possible to get a discount?    A: Hm, since you like it so much, how about a 10 percent discount. That's the best I can offer.    B: That's good.    A: Is there anything else I can get for you, a pair of socks?    B: No, that should be it. Thank you.

triplets.head: heavy wool gloves
triplets.tail: I'd like to have something warm

utterances: A: Hi, are you being helped?    B: No, I'm not. I'm interested in some hats.    A: All our hats are in this section. What do you think of this one here? It's made of cotton.    B: Hmm,it looks nice and is suitable for autumn, but I'd like to have something warm for winter.    A: Maybe you would like a heavy wool hat. How about this one?    B: I think that's what I want. How much is it?    A: It's seventy dollars plus tax.    B: It's a little expensive. Do you think it's possible to get a discount?    A: Hmm, since you like it so much, how about a 10 percent discount. That's the best I can offer.    B: That's good. Could you wrap it up for me?    A: Sure. Is there anything else I can get for you?    B: I also want to have a red wool sweater. But there are only black and green ones.

A: Hi, honey. Do you need any help with your luggage?    B: No, thanks, dad. I just brought one carry-on in my backpack.    A: Great. I wish your mother would take some packing lessons from you. OK, let's go home.    B: Hm...It's cold here.    A: Yes, the weatherman says that it might snow tonight. What temperature was it when you took off from California this morning?    B: Sixty degrees and sunny.    A: Don't you people miss the seasons?    B: Not really. It's nice to go outside everyday. And always have nice sun- ny weather.

A: Hi, what can I do for you?    B: I'd like to send this package to France. Can it be delivered in the next five days?    A: Yes. We offer an overnight service. It'll cost 70 dollars.    B: Ah, that's a bit expensive. Do you have a three-day service?    A: No, but we can get your package to France in one week for 40 dollars.    B: Well, that sounds good. I'll take that. Is the service guaranteed?    A: Yes. We also offer a service where we can track your package. But that will cost 10 dollars extra.    B: Oh, I won't need the tracking service...

triplets.head: expensive
triplets.tail: get your package to France in one week

triplets.head: track your package
triplets.tail: get your package to France in one week

utterances: A: Hi, would you like some free candies?    B: Sure. What are you handing these out for?    A: Well, we're trying to gather some volunteers for the day care center.    B: Uh... A: Tomorrow is Mike's birthday. I have just received the invitation to his party. Did Mike invite you, too?    B: Yes. I received his invitation this morning. B: Please ask him to give me a call as soon as he returns. He has my number.    A: Very well, Mr. Dewey, I'll do that.    B: Thank you. Bye-bye.

A: Waiter, can we have the bill please?    B: Yes, madam. How will you pay for it, with cash or credit card,please?    A: With my Visa Card.    B: I'm awfully sorry, madam. But we only accept American Express and Master Card.    A: In that case, I'll pay with cash then.    B: Thank you, madam.

A: No. At the People's Theatre.    B: If I remember correctly, you put it on at the Youth Square last year.    A: Yeah. But it is under repair now.    B: But why are you doing that? To collect money for repairing the Youth Square?    A: No. We want to collect money and send it to Project Hope.    B: That sounds like a good idea. Good luck to you.    A: Thanks a lot.

utterances: A: What seems to be the matter?    B: I just can't sleep well, doctor.    A: I see. And how long have you had this problem?    B: Oh, for about two weeks now.    A: Two weeks. A: What's going on around here? Why is everyone changing offices?    B: Haven't you heard? Where have you been anyway?    A: I just got back from visiting the plant in Chicago.    B: Well, there are a lot of changes being made here this week.    A: Yes, I see. But what are they?    B: For one thing, Martha and Jim are leaving. utterances: A: We've all heard the saying "Laughter is the best medicine." How important is it to our health, Dr. Berk?    B: This saying has been scientifically proven! A year-long study of heart attack victims done at the Oakhurst Health Research Institute in California found that of those patients who spent half an hour a day watching comedy videos, 10 percent had a second heart attack, whereas 30 percent of those who did not watch had a second attack.    A: Wow! Laughter is really a good medicine to patients. Can you give us another example?    B: Sure! Norman Cousins, editor of the Saturday Review, learned this during a battle with an illness. He discovered that his condition improved when he enjoyed himself and watched funny movies.    A: You said Norman learned this? Do we have to learn to laugh?    B: Not necessarily. Since laughing is something people can do sitting down, costs no money, and requires no special exercise equipment or skill, it's the perfect workout for anyone who doesn't have the time or desire to participate in a regular fitness program.    A: Oh. Do you have such a program to offer to the general public?    B: Yes, we do. It's called the Smile Time-Out. A: What about the situation in which you aren't in a mood to laugh?    B: Even when you fake a smile or laugh, you get the same physiological benefits as when it's the real thing, because your mind is smart, but your body is stupid and can't tell the difference!

utterances: A: Good evening and welcome to this week's Business World, the program for and about business people. Tonight, we have Mr. Steven Kayne, who has just taken over and established bicycle shop. Tell us, Mr. Kayne, what made you want to run yourown store?    B: Well, I always loved racing bikes and fixing them. When I was working full-time as a salesman for a big company, I seldom had time to enjoy my hobby. I knew then that as soon as I had enough money to get my own business going, I'll do it. I had my heart set on it and I didn't let anything stand in my way. When I went down to the bank and got a business loan, I knew I'd love being myown boss. Now my time is my own. I open the store when I want and leave when I want.    A: You mean you don't keep regular hours?    B: Well, the sign on my store says the hours are ten to six, but if business isslower than usual, I can just lock up and take off early.    A: Have you hired any employees to work with you yet?    B: Yeah, a couple of friends of mine who love biking as much as I do. They help me out a few days a week. It's great because we play cards or just sit around and talk when there are no customers.    A: Thank you, Mr. Kayne. We wish you success in your new business.

utterances: A: With us now, is Malcolm Bricklin, CEO of Visionary Vehicles.    B: Hello, everyone.    A: We have been hearing a couple of things about this news that Ford Motor Company is slashing up to 30,000 jobs, shutting down 14 plants nationwide. Is it a big deal if we are no longer manufacturing these cars, Malcolm?    B: I think it's a huge deal. I mean the companies are massive employers both directly and indirectly. If you look at Ford after their restructuring, they've actually got 87,000 employees which is twice as many as Microsoft have worldwide. Moreover, if you look at those jobs, they are very high-paying jobs. These are people who can afford to buy their own products.    A: Er, it seems to indicate a big hit for our economy if these jobs go bye-bye.    B: Yeah, it's a really sad day for America.    A: But it is not as if cars are stopped being made, right?    B: Correct. Still a large number of cars are being made by American manufacturers. More than half of the American cars sold in America are American. So what has happened over time is that as the market share has fallen, foreign car companies have come in, taken over plants and set up new plants, and they have taken over that capacity. So, it is not like there are fewer cars being produced in America than there were 30 years ago.    A: Let me ask you about the Chinese coming in. What would it mean to American jobs, if and when that happens?    B: The Chinese cars we have seen so far aren't that great and they don't have the branding necessary to make a huge impact in the world stage.
